transcript: You know what has been happening since the past 2 years Since the past 2 years In all the videos, 50% of the comments Have 2 words in common Soya Chaap Soya Chaap , like seriously you'll have just been asking for this  So I thought lets just make it today So all the people who are jumping with excitement, hold on cause the music is coming ok So here I am back With soya chaap Hmm Nothing much to do, just make it and eat it  And if you want to eat the best soya chaap, the BEST So there is only one city And its not Delhi Have you ever eaten soya chaap from Chandigarh Have you ever tried it? Go have it from Chandigarh  So lets move on with the show Now there are 2 ways of treating soya chaap Soya chaap So Its base is soya textured protein And now that I have used so many words, so I will explain it to you as well but not now, after some time But in this word "soya textured protein" the word "textured" is very important Its texture is very meaty, which is why this is very famous in Chandigarh and Delhi Sometimes when we cant consume meat and we want that feel that when we  Eat soya chaap Ok Second and the most important thing is that Whenever Whenever you Are working with any textured protein So with respect cook it first only, the biggest mistake people do That they mix the raw proteins in the gravy and later they fail to achieve the texture in it   So to get the texture in it you will have to cook it,  and there are three way to do so So either you can steam it Or you can boil it or fry it So you steam this Or boil this when you want To double cook it  Meaning while you are stuffing it, frying it or making a tandoori or a tikka in that case you should boil it because   Because once its crispy the marination wont go inside it right! but when making a gravy You can steam it and fry it or directly fry it Understanding this part is very important Alright This is the basic fundamental Of soya textured protein and to maintain it you will have to cook it  separately  Alright then So I have thought we will make  Malai soya chaap But not the tandoori malai soya chaap The malai soya chaap with gravy Alright, so to make malai soya chaap with gravy we will need Soya chaap  So what I am going to do here is boil and then fry the soya chaap And boiling and then frying has its own pros and cons The advantage is you can add flavor in it So all the spices and the ginger garlic paste I put while boiling will all get incorporated in to it right! But the disadvantage it that because while boiling water get into the soya chaap so then while frying There are a lot of chances Of it bursting so take care of that Or else you can directly even fry it but with boiling the Flavors will seep till the inside So we were talking about the texture right, that texture is developing right now As and when it cook it develops texture that's why In soya texture protein to develop the texture cooking it very important Alright Now because Because now again We have to fry this Ok That's why I will only Cook this 60% or else it will become dry "Ok hai" Ishaan talks this way Then it ok no papa I can play on the mobile for 10 minutes no So ok for you also no that only cook it this much So we are done with part number one and now   We have to let it dry a little because if we dont let it dry it will explode in the oil And until it cools down and dries Till then you can hear the story of soya textured protein Because soya Is a book in itself So the story of soybean is interesting and it is interesting because Obviously soya bean is not from India, it is from Southeast Asia and from there it went to China Then from China came to India In 1000 AD which means 1000 years It came to India, and until then Indian dint know what soya was And then it failed in India And only a few Northern states grew soya bean And otherwise it never spread around India Until the 1500's When again soya bean came to South India through Japan And From there people came to know what is soya bean but then it failed again Because it used to take a lot of time to cook And We Indian's were not able to understand that taste so In Indian soya bean took 3 entries In 1000 AD In 1660 approximately And in 1832 And all the 3 times it completely failed And it got success in 1960 when People understood the technique of extracting soya bean oil and then after the extraction the wastage that was left  So the thing that we got by grinding that wastage is the soya textured proteins that we also call soya chunks, soya chaap, soya keema So all of these are basically A way of using the leftover after removing oil, but it is nutritious you know how they say to eat the fruit and sell the seeds So lets keep them big in size, 1/2 types That's it this was the secret of that famous chaap from Chandigarh Ya if you mention words like secrets, then the videos do very wee, really I am telling you So now you can either deep fry it or if you want Shallow fry it in lots of oil, the benefit of shallow frying it in a lot of oil is   That you can add flavor to that oil, flavor like black caramom Or dry red chili or bay leaf, that we are going to add So you should never leave a chance of adding flavor to food Either it may be boiling or frying Every time you touch food, it is an opportunity to add flavor but  Never overdo it, you should know where to stop Ok so see the first part is ready In this part remember Where ever you can add taste add it  Ok now the second part Now we have to make the gravy The gravy is very simple So I am showing you a very basic malai gravy After which you wont have to look left or right   Here I am keeping everything chunky but I will strain it later, so nothing will come in your mouth  You should only get the flavor, this is our habit (Lucknow people) The gravy should only have flavor and not spices Both black and green cardamom 3 cloves Black peppercorns Ok there are the spices and we already have bay leaf Now add the ghee Once the black pepper goes in the oil It will explode Cloves and black pepper are basically oil bombs So please be very careful Or else you will go to make malai chaap And end up in the dispensary And then you will say Ranveer you dint tell us, now goes the curd And some cashew paste And we will add some cream now and some later, the cream is optional you can even add malai Whishing is very very important because If you wont whish it the curd may split When ever you make a curd based gravy always whisk it, I have told you'll so many times right! Look this part is very important It is important because The cooking of the curd Is very very very important If there is rawness remaining in the curd then it will keep souring with time and it does not taste good It should be sour but not too much Now I am adding another secret ingredient in this This is a very big secret It is coriander stem It will slowly leave the flavor in this and if you get coriander root Wash it properly, grind it and then add it in Even that gives a very good taste in a white gravy Now I am adding sugar, its optional Alright the ghee has come up That means we can strain this  And it is very spicy I have already tasted it  Because of the green chili So people wont understand how is white gravy so spicy Extract the whole flavor Of the spices The ginger The green chili There you go The malai gravy is ready Perfect So the gravy is ready, I am adding some water why Because once our chaap goes in this We have fried it And because of frying It has become dry and thirsty so they will drink the gravy That's why thin down the gravy a little Second if the gravy will be then then only it will be soaked, it will go till inside See now you get the malai feel Now just dont leave this like this, so at least 10 minutes Cook it in the gravy For the garnish Ginger, green chili and a special masala And for the special mixture you need 3 things Dried fenugreek leaves Black pepper powder and black cardamom powder Should I eat it or not Yours is here come take it, I am eating You have asked for this recipe with so much rampancy Now that I have made it  Do try it  Other wise now on I will stop eating malai chaap And please do subscribe Otherwise you will stop getting malai chaap in your city

title: ‡§ò‡§∞ ‡§™‡§∞ ‡§¨‡§ø‡§®‡§æ ‡§§‡§Ç‡§¶‡•Ç‡§∞ ‡§ï‡•á ‡§™‡§®‡•Ä‡§∞ ‡§ü‡§ø‡§ï‡•ç‡§ï‡§æ | Paneer Tikka recipe | Paneer Tikka No Tandoor | Chef Ranveer
description: PANEER TIKKA BINA TANDOOR - Panner Tikka is one of the most common food of choice at the restaurant and this video breaks ...
transcript: Thanks to social media, I get alot of request Right? And do you know which requests do I get the most? Please teach us, how to make Paneer tikka just like its made in Tandoor! Now, to make a Tandoor like Paneer Tikka you require a Tandoor. And you also require the restaurant like marination And I think that's where we fail at home! Because at home, not everyone has a Tandoor! And then the restaurant style marination recipe! Let me make it easy for you. We will do a Paneer Tikka recipe, actually I'll make two types! It's very simple. So the base for the Paneer Tikka marination is yogurt Ginger Garlic paste After that Kasuri methi (Dried fenugreek leaves) which will be divided in two parts One part we added here And the other part, we'll add later In garnish Ok, after this Mustard oil This has been mixed Nice Salt Very little carom seeds Now to thicken this Roasted gram flour So, you can either roast gram flour Or you can grind roasted chick peas into a flour And yes, most importantly.. if the yogurt is tangy then great If the yogurt is not tangy, then you can add little lemon juice Here the curd is tangy, so I'm not adding lemon juice. This is a base marination Now you can do anything with this marination For example Take one part, add saffron Kesari Paneer Tikka Take the second part Add degi mirch (Degi red chilli powder) Regular paneer tikka Take one part, add green spice mix Haryali Paneer Tikka Take one part, add achaar (Pickle) Achaari (Pickeld)Paneer Tikka It's actually as simple as that! Here for now, i'll make two types In one i'll add degi red chilli powder Alot of people have asked me if Degi Red Chilli powder is a type of chilli? No Degi Red Chilli powder is not a variety of chilli Degi Chilli is blend of chillies And this second one, i'll make it achaari (Pickled) Achaari (Pickled) Paneer Tikka So here goes the pickle This is Pachranga Pickle Best is to use Pachranga pickle only for Achaari Paneer Tikka Here we have added this And very little turmeric powder Right, so you have two kinds of marinations One yellow marination And one red marinaton Lets add the vegetables After this, paneer (Cottage Cheese) Now in the other one Now, mix this with a light hand Over here, doing it with hands will be a better idea And now the red one Now just add these to the skewer Okay? First the hard vegetables This is very important Adding more paneer in between is fine, but on the sides adding vegetables is important as it acts as an anchor and holds the paneer! Or else the paneer will slide away quickly Mustard oil And it's very important to smoke the mustard oil. If it won't be smoked, the real taste will never come. Whenever you cook with mustard oil, either use it raw or smoke it And once it's smoked, i'll add little butter It's Punjabi food, it won't be made without butter! Here we add butter! Now on top of this adding very little butter is important If you don't add the butter, you won't get the taste Remember, good things in life always have butter in them. No no, I won't ever waste ghee (clarified butter), don't worry In our house, ghee is never wasted! I will do the plating Thinly sliced onion (Laccha Pyaaz) All set The biggest problem of cooking in oven or pan The biggest problem is, you don't get the aroma of Tandoor! That smokey smell doesn't come! Right? Now what to do? There's  a way to bring the smokey smell And that way is, this coal Here goes the coal And on top of it Here goes the ghee I mean, no need to show off so much Once the tikka is ready, you can generally add coal to it so the smokeyness comes Here it is just a way of presenting! By the time it reaches the table, the smell of tandoor smoke will be filled in the dish This just needs to be opened And eaten! And yeah, if you want you can sprinkle a little bit of Kasuri Methi (dried fenugreek leaves) again The tandoor is made! And very little dried fenugreek leaves(Kasuri Methi) And some Little bit lemon here It's done? Simple, easy, Tandoor like Paneer Tikka Restaurant style Paneer Tikka at home! And it didn't even take time! Cooking is actually that simple! Isn't it?

transcript: Hello everyone and welcome to my kitchen the K Kitchen.   Today in the K Kitchen we are making Paneer Tikka. In order to make Paneer Tikka, first, we have to cut the Cottage Cheese(Paneer). So I‚Äôm cutting the paneer into 4 pieces. And we can further cut it into smaller pieces. Now, whenever we make Paneer Tikka, many times what happens is that a lot of chaat masala is drizzled on the top So the upper layer becomes very salty, while the Paneer is bland from inside. To avoid that, we need to marinate the paneer with some salt and some Chilli powder. And keep this in a warm place. Due to this, the salt will sweep in and the Cheese will lose a little water. Just toss and turn it in Salt and Chilli. And as it leaves water it gets more firm, which means it won‚Äôt break during the preparation. We have this hung Yogurt. To this Yogurt, we add a little Salt, a little Ginger and Garlic paste, a little freshly chopped coriander and that's it. Now we need to prepare the marination for this Paneer Tikka. For the marination, we heat up a pan. And I have mustard oil, not too much. Mustard oil is hot. We don't have to smoke up the mustard oil, just need it to be really hot, that's all. In this hot oil goes Carom seeds, chopped green Chillies and chopped ginger. There. Just cook it lightly. Now to this, I am adding one spoon Gram flour, and we will lightly saut√© this. We have to roast the gram flour in mild heat, because it is just a spoon of gram flour, it will cook very quickly. Just about 2-3 minutes. At this stage, we w ill add some turmeric and turn off the heat, a nice stir. Now we just need to whisk it together. Now you need to understand. The Gram Flour keeps the oil together, The Gram Flour keeps the oil together, means it binds it together. Otherwise when it‚Äôs heated, all the marinate will slip off with the oil. So, Gram flour is very critical. Alright. We have Peppers, Onions, Tomatoes. We will cut their Shashlik, that is we dice them. And we inter layer them with the Cheese. Alright, I am cutting it into thick chunks. And to the insides, you can just slide your knife and remove them. They have no taste actually. Taste is in this fleshy Pepper. Same with Onions. We need big chunks of onions and just peel them away like this. It's actually so simple and so easy. Now we have the marinade, we have our paneer. Just lightly rub the marinade on the paneer. Marinate the paneer nicely. There. Now the vegetables, again just slightly marinate them. You don't have to salt the vegetables. Alright. we have the skewers, time to. Skewer these. So take nice red pepper, our paneer tikka, onion, green pepper and we will keep this aside. Again in no particular order just skewer them. And it is done, one tip before you start grilling the Paneer Shaslik. Always clean the Shaslik or the saut√© stick off any excess marinade. What will happen is that, as you start to cook, the marination will also starts cooking. And then it will become oily, greasy and dirty. And when you hold it, It won‚Äôt be neat. So make sure this is clean. So some oil And on a hot grill just need to place this. Listen to the sound of food, the other. Now, till this Paneer Tikka gets ready we will prepare a quick dip for it. I have an onion. Onion goes in there. Now, we will add some freshly chopped mint, a lot of mint actually. Some green Chillies for the heat, a little lemon. Some salt And some mayonnaise. So this will become like a mint mayonnaise. There. This is done. First of all, we will add the dip. Fill it up. Now what we need to do is. Place our skewers onto this platter. I think they look beautiful and they taste yum. Alright, restaurant-style Paneer Tikka Shaslik with a Mint Mayonnaise is done.

title: ‡§∏‡§ø‡§∞‡•ç‡§´ 3‡§ö‡•Ä‡•õ‡•ã ‡§∏‡•á ‡§π‡§≤‡§µ‡§æ‡§à ‡§ú‡•à‡§∏‡•Ä ‡§ï‡•Å‡§∞‡§ï‡•Å‡§∞‡•Ä ‡§ú‡§≤‡•á‡§¨‡•Ä Perfect Easy Kurkuri Jalebi Recipe Instant Jalebi ki Recipe
description: Jalebi Recipe #jalebirecipe #jalebi #instantjalebirecipe #howtomakejalebiathome #bestjalebirecipe #crispyjalebirecipe Jalebi ...
transcript: (Music) Today, we will prepare Holi special crispy jalebi. You don't need to do hard work or wait for hours to make this. No tension of fermentation, corn flour,baking soda or powder. Within 10 minutes jalebi ready with only 3 ingredients. Special thing is you will get the market style jalebi taste. You will be overjoy when you eat this. Before starting the video, I am requesting to you all. If you like my video then like and share. Don't forget to subscribe yours channel Cook With Parul. We will make syrup first to make crispy and juicy Jalebi. Take pan which has depth like this. Take 2 cup sugar. Set 1 cup and make measurements with that. 2 cup means, I took 425gm sugar. Add 1 cup water. Ratio should be 2:1 Let the sugar dissolve properly on medium flame. Add little cardamom powder for flavour. Add little saffron strands. It is totally optional. It gives good colour and aroma to jalebi. Mix well. It take less time to make jalebi. Watch full video, I will tell you every detail. It is so simple to make. To give good colour to jalebi, Halwayi adds food colour. These kind of colour easily available in the market. Take any of this and add kesariya food colour. I added food colour here to make market style. You can use turmeric as well, if you want to skip colour. We need little string syrup. Let me show you. Keep little syrup in your finger. It is little sticky. Consistency of syrup should be like this. If you make thick then jalebi will not able to absorb syrup. If it will thin then jalebi will become soft. We should need this consistency for crispy jalebi. Add few drops of lemon juice. Syrup will not be sour by it will not become crystalize. Syrup will remain shiny and glazy. Keep this aside and let's make jalebi batter. Take a pot and add 1 cup all purpose flour. I am telling you this recipe simply with all purpose flour. You will get the taste of market style fermented jalebi. 1 cup all purpose flour means I took 150gm. I am adding 1tbsp clarified butter for good moyan. You can use oil as well. Rub it so that flour mix properly. So that jalebi will prepare crispy. Comment and tell ,which is your favourite dish of Holi. Which next dish, you want to learn from me. Add water gradually and make a thick batter of it. Mix this with whisker or fork. We should make lumps free batter of medium consistency. How properly you will whisk more crispy jalebi  become. Your mouth gets watery by only calling name of jalebi. Smooth batter is ready with thick consistency. To ferment and make fluffy jalebi, add 1 sachet of eno. 1 sachet is equal to 1tsp. You can use any fruit salt. I shared jalebi recipe with curd and soda earlier. You can try it also. Curd and soda also works as fruit salt. This is so instant because generally eno available at home. Add water on this and it is activated now. Mix well. Fermentation in jalebi batter is done. When you drop this, you will get ribbon shape. We need this consistency. Let's make jalebi now. To make Jalebi, take this type of bottle with nozzle like this. You can use washed empty milk packet by making a hole. If you have piping bag like this, then fill in this. You can use zip lock bag as well.  I told you all the option,make as per your convenient I am using piping bag, you can use milk packet as well. Fill batter in this. Make a cut after filling batter in the cone. Take a broad pan like this for frying jalebi. Don't over fill oil. It should be 1/4 of pan. Put a few drops in oil and see, it is flaoting. We  need this much hot oil. Remove this now. Now, rotate cone like this. Give random design to it, just like we put henna. Only put that much jalebi, how much space is available. Keep the flame medium. After putting jalebi, keep flame low and let it be cook. Don't touch it now. When it becomes little firm then flip. In first batch, may be you'll not get design but in second batch you will get. We don't make everyday so it takes time to make design. It is so simple. Make with cone or bottle. Second point, heat oil on medium flame, then make jalebi. If you fry jalebi in cold oil then it will become flat. If you fry on hot oil then it will red and soft after frying. It is most important point for crispy jalebi. They coming up itself and become firm. Flip it on this stage. Fry till golden colour come from both side. Keep jalebi in the syrup instantly after frying. Only then jalebi will absorb sugar syrup. If you add later the it will absorb syrup from inside. We should should dip jalebi for 40-60 seconds in hot syrup. Press it little and syrup will be fill itself. It will become soft if you keep it for long time. If you want to eat crispy then dip in syrup for long time. Take out jalebi in few seconds. Do I need to say anything. Colour is changed. Our jalebi is prepared so tempting. Crispy and same in taste. Colour is changed, that means syrup is filled perfectly. It is still crispy, didn't turn soft yet. I will show you that how crispy it is with these jalebi. Now, you understood that it is perfect jalebi. (Crackle sound) We will second batch of jalebi like this. You will enjoy while making this. (Music) Let me show you its crisp before serving. Not a single jalebi is soft. Crisp is there and syrup as well. Isn't it perfect. Do prepare on Holi for family members. Give everyone surprise of Jalebi. Our Holi special crispy halwayi style Jalebi is ready. Fill happiness of sweet on Holi. Do follow my tips, Your jalebi will become perfect 100%. Then you don't want buy from outside and make at home. Jalebi is looking tempting, let's garnish this with pistachios. Or serve like this only. Tell me in comments, how you prepared instant jalbei. Friends, if you like my video and hard work then like and share. Don't forget to subscribe yours channel Cook With Parul. You can see details of my recipes on my website cookwithparul.com Thank you for watching Cook With Parul. Jai Hind Jai Bharat.

Hello there!
Hello! Hello! Hello! There's a common saying in Punjabi which means
 the comfort given by dal roti is simply unbeatable! Actually, the person who recited this would've 
changed it after having my today's recipe.  Welcome! I am Ranveer Brar and meet me after 
the music for an amazing Dal Bati or Dal Bafla recipe! Shall we start?
Let's do it! To cook Baflas, we'll need a thick flour.  Normally, people add shortening along with other spices to make Baflas  But I thought of modifying the recipe! So for masala bati or bafla,  I'm going to use the same clarified butter 
that will be used for the tempered shortening.  I'm too smart, right? Food that is cooked happily is always the best! People from Malva, please don't be mad at me for adding
 cumin seeds into it. If you wish, you can skip this step. Malva is nearby Rajasthan, It contains the regions of Ratlam, Ujjain and Indore,  The cuisine of Malva is wholesome! Dishes like Ratlami sev, poha and jalebi are 
famous in the regions of Ujjain, Indore and Ratlam Evidently, if you're adding hot tempered shortening into the flour,  You can't mix it with your hands, right? It's important to add shortening in the beginning 
as it makes the dough flaky and tasty.  ¬º cup of shortening is enough for 1 cup of flour.  Don't look at me like that!
I'm on a strike! I won't cook until you subscribe to my channel and press the bell icon.  I'm sorry for the interruption.  Add half a spoon of baking soda into this It will enhance the rise of the dough. Hot tempered clarified butter has filled the kitchen with its aroma! That's all I can think about! Curd makes the dough fluffly.  Keep the dough a little runny as semolina will soak up the remaining water.  If you knead a tight dough, 
you won't be able to handle it later And then you'll say, "Ranveer, you did not tell us!" But Ranveer already told you that semolina will soak up a lot of water.  That's why, keep the dough soft.  Let's start making the dal.  You can cook it in 2 ways.  First, you prepare a tempering, add dal into it and cook all of it together.  Second, you can boil the dal separately, add it into the tempering and cook it together.  Which method do you prefer?
The first one, right? It will be a one pot recipe.
Why should we make the recipe tedious? Onion and garlic is optional in this recipe.  You can simply add ginger into it.  I don't like using garlic but you can add some if you wish.  Chop the onions as finely as possible without hurting yourself! We're not participating in a race, are we? I'm using 2 cups of dal that isn't soaked. You can chop the tomatoes in a mini chopper as well. 
You remember our mini chopper, right? It doesn't require electricity at all! Pour some clarified butter and some oil into the utensil. The dal is soaked and thoroughly washed.  I threw away the dirty water after washing the dal.  I'm going to use chana dal and toor dal for this recipe.  Please be careful when you add black peppercorns
 and cloves because they will start spluttering.  Add onions and keep cooking the onions.  I know everyone will start commenting, "Ranveer! 
You did not add that ingredient into this!" Whole red chillies!
I'll directly add it into the tempering! Clarified butter and whole red chillies.  I tell you everything.
I don't keep any secrets from you! It's so beautiful! Add a pinch of asafoetida,  Degi red chilli powder,  Some turmeric powder,  Coriander powder,  As soon as you smell the aroma of cooked coriander powder, add the tomatoes. All you need to do is thoroughly cook the tomatoes.  In an another pan, I'm going to roast some sesame seeds and peanuts.  Keep a lid handy because sesame seeds start spluttering a lot.
Add some salt to make sure that it gets roasted well. You can see my entire kitchen in its reflection! Can you please grind it?
Keep it coarsely.  Add dal into this.  Soaking and thoroughly washing the dal is equally important.  Here's chana dal  And here's toor dal.  This is the first method of cooking this recipe Where we add the dal into the tempering along
 with some water and cook everything together.  The sweet and sour flavour for this dal recipe is very important.  People from Indore prefer a sweet and sour dal. For that, you can either add some tamarind water or some ketchup.  Some add jaggery into it.  I'm going to add some lemon juice into it in the end.  As soon as the fats starts separating,
Add water into it, close the lid and let it cook.  Give me the powder! Here goes our powder! If you're having this recipe in Indore, 
then the aroma of peanuts and sesame seeds is its monopoly.  Without this the recipe of Dal Bafla is incomplete! Add some salt, close the lid and let it cook.  Don't go home yet, 
We still have to cook Baflas! Let's move ahead with the process Divide the dough into 3 equal dough balls.  I'll tell you the reason behind it later.  Do this to the first doughball.  Then the second doughball and then the third doughball! This gives the Bafla a paratha like layers. You can use a rolling pin as well. 
You don't have to work so hard like I am! Ranveer couldn't work out for a very long time so
 he thought of this way but you don't have to do this! Cut it into equal sized pieces.  Then make small Baflas out of it. If you wish, you can make bigger Baflas as well.  Keep the Baflas round if you're going to use an oven.  But if you're going to use a pan, then make them
 a little flatter and make a small dent in the middle.  The dent may disappear when the Baflas fluff up but that's alright! It's good that it is breaking apart!
It's a sign of a good Bafla! You can also... Why Should I tell you everything now?
You'll simply start skipping the video! Nowadays, you don't care about our friendship! Everyone starts skipping the video! Let the Baflas rest for a while, 
It will make the Baflas more fluffy! Our dal is almost done!
It's first class! Make it a little thinner by adding some hot water into it.  You can cook it in 2 ways.  You can either steam it or you can poach it.  Basically, you can either cook it with steam or with water. To steam it, you can place a strainer or a stand in the utensil.  Or you can place a metal sifter upside down in the utensil.  You can steam it that way as well! Second, I'll show you how to poach it.  You can use a patila as well but I'm using a flat
 utensil to make sure that you can see it properly.  Grease it with oil or clarified butter.  Keep some space between the Baflas as they will start fluffing up due to baking soda.  Close its lid.  While poaching the Balfas, add some salt into it.  You can add some ginger and green chillies into 
the water to make the Baflas more flavourful! Don't boil the water.
Make it warm.  While steaming, it may start cracking up but that's the monopoly of the dish! Close the lid and let it cook.  This is poaching and this is steaming.  Poaching cannot be done in boiling water.  You're not supposed to boil the water. 
You're supposed to make the water warmer.  Basically, it should bubble a little.  It should start simmering.  And look how steamed Baflas have started fluffing up! Basically, wait until the Baflas start floating.
Remove them as soon as they start floating.  Basically, if you directly bake the bati, it becomes hard. 
It's known as bati because it is hard.  Baflas are soft!
That is why I like this more! This stem is important for poached Baflas to enhance their texture.  You can either shallow fry or deep fry the Baflas! In indore, huge Baflas are poached and then deep fried in clarified butter! It should be crispy from outside and soft from inside.
If it isn't crispy, then it won't taste good.  Crispy and fluffy! You can't get this texture if you directly bake the Baflas!
You'll lose all the moisture.  This is amazing!
I'm having fun! Slow down the flame and get a grill.  If you wish, you can do the same with the steamed Baflas Or you can simply roast them. Here you go!
It's pure magic! My wife is going to complain about this! Look at this closely!
This is the real monopoly! You can either steam or poach your Baflas.  But I prefer steaming because it keeps the nutrients intact. 
Your Baflas may lose some of its nutrients while you poach them. You can either cook it on a pan or you can directly roast them on your gas stove.  Your wish, 
your Bafla! You can use an oven as well!
Cook it on high heat till it is a little darker! Basically, I've taught you how to cook it and finish it in multiple ways! Now you can't say, "Ranveer, you did not tell us!" I won't give you a chance! We are friends but I won't give you a chance to complain at all! I won't let you say, "Ranveer, you did not tell us!" It has started looking so pretty! Cook it on a slow gas and cook it for a long time! Double cooking is very important as it gives a structure to the dish! Let me introduce you to our clarified butter! Here's our boiled Bafla, steamed Bafla or Tawa fried,  And here goes our steamed Bafla! Look how beautiful the texture looks! Wow Ranveer Brar!  You've made me so proud! No kidding, this is beautiful! The monopoly of this dish is clarified butter Let's start finishing the dal! Remove the whole spices, Add some hot water.
Don't add boiling water into this.  It will hamper the colour of the dish,  Add warm water into it.  The dal should neither be too thick nor too thin.  Reduce the dal to enhance the taste and texture of the dish! I'll proceed further as soon as the dal starts boiling.  I'll reduce it a little more As soon as the cumin starts spluttering, add red chillies into it.  Make the red chillies super crispy! Add the tempering into the dal! This is so beautiful! This looks so beautiful! I have represented every type of bati on the plate! If you can have onions, then you can serve it with some onions. Or you can serve it with pickles.  If you're having Rajasthani Dal Bati, then onions are compulsory! But this Dal Bafla is from Malva, that's why I haven't used onions into this.  If you wish, you can skip adding onions into the recipe.  You can simply start with the tempering of 
cumin seeds and then add tomatoes into it.  As I said earlier, you can add some lemon juice in the beginning Or you can add some in the end Or you can serve it with a lemon wedge. It's so bready! Pour some dal on top of it and savour it! Add some lemon juice into it.  Otherwise, you can make the dal a little more sour.  I have made myself super proud! I was not expecting this! I don't expect you to subscribe to my channel! But if you can, please do!

description: Learn how to make Dal Bati Churma at home with chef Varun Inamdar on Rajshri Food. Dal Bati Churma is a Rajasthani famous ...
transcript: subscribe to Raji food and click on the Bell icon for more updates as much as Rajasthan is known for its Rich cultural heritage is also known for its food that one thing that prominently comes to everyone's Minds is definitely a dalbati churma today let's make it the Dal in this case is a very typical Rajasthani Dal which is also known as a Dal punch mail or a punch Mei Dal for that of course punch means five and it's a mixture of five dals the first one is masur DAL red lentils then there is ur Dal we have Chana Dal Mo Dal and tur Dal or arhar Dal well the recipe is there in the description box below so please follow that what I have done for now is I've taken a mixture of these five dolls according to the recipe I have boiled this or rather pressure cooked this just with water no salt no turmeric nothing the next step is to of course give it a TKA and for that we need to heat a pan and to this let's add in ghee this is dacy ghee the tempering of this Dal is going to as classic as it can get the first thing in ghee that goes is cumin seeds or jira well I love lots of jira let's follow that with Hing or asaa chopped garlic and along with this chopped green chilies again lots of them let's give this a mix while the garlic has just begun to change its color lower the flame and let's add in turmeric along with red chili powder let's give this a mix and to this let's add in a boiled doll mix this well well to this D you could also add in onions and tomatoes and things like that I'm adding in tomatoes and finally coriander [Music] leaves and allow this to simmer on low flame for a minimum of 5 to 7 Minutes one last ingredient of course which is the most critical of them all and that is salt as required allow this to simmer and while that's happening let's make the bti for the bti the most important ingredient is wheat flour we need to get the wheat flour which is slightly grainy not as smooth as you make it for a roti or a chapati to this let's add in some salt as required for the bodyy to be nice crusty yet short crust at the same time we need to add in ghee we need to mix this well till it's nice and almost like breadcrumbs and by using water you need to make a nice and soft dough go slow go steady but make sure the dough becomes nice and soft because this is DAL punch mail it has tendency to stick at the bottom so ensure that it keeps stirring even while you're making the body with this your dough for the body is done and ready allow this to rest for somewhere around 10 minutes and then let's move forward the BTY dough has rested well let's give that a quick check and this needs to be divided into lemon sized [Music] balls something like this ensure that this also gets pinched well there's another trick that I learned from someone in Rajasthan and that is just pressing this lightly and dividing it like so but what happens with this it it gets a little natural indentation and then finally you bring all of this together what happens when you do this is the inside becomes a little porous or Hollow and the cooking becomes easier bring all of this together make it nice smooth and free of any cracks and crevices and similarly let's roll the other [Music] bities our btis are rolled and ready let's now move on to the next step and that is baking the btis now traditionally there are various ways of doing this you could do this on a Chula you can do this on a tandur but of course we do not have that in our home kitchens what I can do is I can show you a gas trick where you place this on a gas you of course create a little bit of an elevation place this and allow these to bake till they're nice golden brown and a little charred here and there on all the sides these bities need to be baked on low to medium flame constantly and this is going to take a good 15 to 20 minutes so patience here is going to be a virtue our baries look perfectly baked and ready let's transfer these into a bowl well what I'm doing at this stage is I'm dividing these into two different bowls there's one bowl which has lots of ghee and that is going to be for the body and these that is without the ghee I'm allowing these to cool down completely because the next step is by using this and that is making the chura this is an extremely important step in the making of bti and that is soaking the btis in ghee the next step is moving towards making the churma for this I'm taking these roasted bities and grinding these into a horse [Music] powder well that's how it looks for the chura I'm going to heat a pan and add in a tablespoon full of Ky again allow the ghee to heat while the ghee is getting heated let's add in a few PODS of crushed green cardamom to this let's add in a powdered bti or which is now the chura along with this let's add in your slivers of almonds mix this well and toast this till it's nice fragrant and nutty off course the flame and let's transfer this into another Bowl one final step to complete the chura and that is adding in Bora or powdered sugar give this a mix and with this the three components that is DAL bti and chura are done and ready let's now move on to the plating [Music] and with this your dalbati chura is done and ready now that you have a detailed recipe for dalbati churma invite your friends over for a dalbati churma party trust me is going to be absolutely worth it do not forget to like and share the video and subscribe to R food

potatoes wash them nice and clean peel off the skin chop them into medium sized pieces and keep them in a bowl of water till you cook them take a nice wide pan or a kadai add about two tablespoons of oil add one teaspoon of cumin seeds about three red chilies add about 2 medium sliced onions finely chopped saute the onions for about 2 to 3 minutes once the onions are transparent add 1 tablespoon of ginger garlic and green chilli paste saute it along with the onions next add the potato pieces mix it well add one teaspoon of salt half teaspoon turmeric powder and mix everything next add 2 medium sized tomatoes finely chopped mix it along with the potatoes now add 1 tsp of chili powder 1 teaspoon cumin powder and 1 teaspoon garam masala powder mix it along with all the potatoes [Music] now add about half cup of water mix everything well close the pot and let it cook for about 10 minutes after 10 minutes let's check on the potatoes i'm going to season it with another teaspoon of salt title: Aloo Palak Ki Sabji | ‡§Ü‡§≤‡•Ç ‡§™‡§æ‡§≤‡§ï ‡§ï‡•Ä ‡§∏‡•ç‡§µ‡§æ‡§¶‡§ø‡§∑‡•ç‡§ü ‡§∏‡§¨‡•ç‡§ú‡§º‡•Ä | Aloo Palak Saag | Kunal Kapur Veg Recipes
transcript:
What a beautiful thing spinach is. Earlier when my mother used to cook it, we
used to make faces and now I wish to eat more and more unique dishes made with spinach. And especially in winters Green leafy vegetables
are quite abundant. spinach, Fenugreek sorrel, dill and amaranth
leaves, all these vegetables are very comforting and they are also very nutritious and nourishing. Today we are going to make aloo palak. A tasty and tangy spinach vegetable. In this you can add any seasonally available
greens like sorrel, dill along with spinach amaranth leaves. The good part is that it is a homemade recipe
which I will be sharing with you all. Let's make aloo palak.. First of all we are going to heat some oil. If you wish you can also use some ghee. It will taste just as good. Once the oil has heated up we are going to
add dried red chillies, these are Kashmiri red chillies so they will impart a good red
colour and it won't impart piquancy. It's optional to add asafoetida and for someone
who doesn't like it can avoid it but it gives a really nice flavour. Chilli, asafoetida and garlic are a combination
made in heaven. The combination of chilli and garlic is a
combination that is encouraged around the world like in America. and even in india the flavour of chilli and
garlic is too good to be true. The garlic has just browned up now, in this
we are going to add a little bit of cumin. Actually I forgot to add it when the oil heated
up because I was talking while cooking but no worries I'll add it now. And now goes in the onion and we have to roast
it And together with onion we can add a little
bit of ginger and chopped green chillies as per your taste. If you are making it for children you can
always avoid adding green chillies. In the meantime I am cutting up some potatoes. To be honest the story of potatoes is quite
interesting. Portuguese came to India and brought potatoes
along with them And during that time the Britishers were ruling
india. In some places, they had been busy trading
and some places had already been invaded by them. So in the northern region specially near Dehradun,
Britishers had already established the farming of potatoes and the biggest market which was
created for selling potatoes was in India itself. People were actually quite fond of potatoes
and there was a time when potatoes were quite expensive because it was an exotic vegetable
back then and was a newcomer in the market. And during that time whole potatoes were added
to the biryani in Kolkata. They were added as a whole because it was
to showcase the addition of exotic vegetables And people who were very wealthy were the
only ones who could afford to eat a potato. And over a period of time potato was proved
to be a nutritious and nourishing vegetable and also became cheaper with time. In the whole world, potatoes are cultivated,
have different varieties and breeds and there are many dishes made with it. We do not have to completely brown the onions. As soon as they start to change their colour,
we are going to add our dry spices into it. First things first we are going to add turmeric
powder, then red chilli, coriander powder then we will give it a quick stir. Just a quick Stir. Now just look at it, the whole thing has evolved
into something beautiful. Now before the spices get burnt we are going
to add tomatoes into it. Give this a good toss. And in here goes the salt. Because of this, tomatoes will release their
water quickly. What a beautiful stage this is in. And we have to cook tomatoes on a high flame
for 2 to 3 minutes. Even if it‚Äôs not completely mashy it‚Äôs
not a problem. At This stage we will add our potatoes
While making this dish you have to use raw potato as when it cooks with the masala, it
will release its own flavour. At the same time, there is no need of boiling
the spinach and cutting it as it will be added raw and will cook with the potatoes and these
two will impart a good flavour when they are cooked raw. Don‚Äôt believe me ? Try making this recipe
and the entire recipe is given below in the description. The ingredients are there, the quantity is
there and at the same time if you want the detailed recipe then you can visit the website(link
in description). Please visit and watch. In this I‚Äôm adding dry kasoori methi and
if you‚Äôre making this in the season and you are getting fresh fenugreek then just
a little bit of fresh fenugreek will give a great taste. Perfect Methi aloo, good combination. Until the potato gets ready let‚Äôs move to
the spinach. If the steaks of the spinach are too thick
then we will snap it off but when it is thin it, just like this it will work. Even this will work as it is sensitive.Look
at this it is sensitive and thin so we can use this. We have to break this thick one and separate
it from the leaf like this now this leaf goes in the side It‚Äôll take some time to break off the leaves
from the stems so till then I will give some tips on how to buy spinach. Watch carefully tips and tricks Spinach leaves are very nutritious and it
is said that for the first time spinach was first grown in Persia, which is modern day
Iran and from there travelled to India. While buying spinach you need to be careful
about certain things like when the leaves have a dark green colour, it indicates that
the spinach is of good quality unlike light green coloured spinach. Sometimes the bunch of spinach has yellow
leaves or is rotten, at that time avoid buying that bunch. If the stems are rotten from below, it means
the spinach has grown old. While buying spinach, when you fold the leaf
lightly and press it, it should snap and break. And if it‚Äôs sifting and limping, that means
the spinach is not fresh. And another thing if the bunch has too many
small or medium sized leaves, then that‚Äôs great because the extra large leaves usually
have a bitter aftertaste. There is also a unique way of washing the
spinach, open the bunch, take a bowl of cold water and immerse the leaves into it, then
move it around with your hands and let them be for 5 minutes. What happens here is, all the sand or dirt
will due to its heaviness settle at the bottom. The leaves float at the top so after that
take the leaves out of the water from the top and keep them aside. If you flip the bowl over with the spinach
and water together then what will happen is the sand will again stick to the leaves. Repeat the process over two times which will
completely clean the spinach. This will avoid any dirt or sand from entering
the mouth. After washing the spinach, if you want to
store it then lightly pat dry the spinach to remove excess water and after that put
it inside a container which has holes. Then you can place it in the fridge. And spinach should never be placed in an airtight
container. So these were our tips and tricks for buying
spinach, let‚Äôs move on with the recipe now. Aloo Palak might be waiting for us. Hold the spinach like this lightly and cut
it into thick slices just like this. So the spinach is ready, let‚Äôs go to the
potatoes now. So right now the potatoes should completely
be cooked, look closely if I press the potato it cuts easily without any resistance. This means the potato is cooked and ready. Now increase the flame and on a high flame
we‚Äôll add the spinach on top of the potato. When you use 10 bowls of spinach that are
cut like this, all you get is 1 cup of spinach as it shrinks and reduces. It looks like you‚Äôre adding too much spinach
which might fall off the pan, don‚Äôt worry nothing like this will happen. Look at those colours, bright green and the
yellow colour of turmeric below it. Slowly all this spinach will settle down. Right now you can add mustard (fresh) or any
other freshly leafy vegetable you like. Have it with a phulka or a lachha paratha
and if you want the recipe of lachha paratha then visit the link in the description, it
Very simple and easy. The spinach cooks easily and really fast so
keep in mind, cook it on high flame until it loses all its water. What a lovely looking dish, aloo Palak. The dish is ready, let‚Äôs plate the aloo
Palak. Here the Aloo Palak goes into the roti and
makes a great roll. And Aloo Palak, done.

hello namaste salaamwalekum satsriyakaal; welcome back to another session with your VahChef at Vahrehvah.com. You know for the vegetarians there are various variations that they
make with Palak and potato, today I'm going to show you one very simple
variation. For this take oil in a pan first for the tempering add mustard seeds let the mustard seed splutter, add cumin
seeds and hing, add ginger garlic paste and I've cut the potatoes into really
small pieces and then put it in the water so that they won't discolor. add
just the potatoes and do not add the water here. Now add turmeric, I added little
extra oil in this dish you know in villages there they eat more of rice and less of curry that is when they use a little extra oil and they can
take a little less of the curry and then mix it with more amount of rice still it tastes awesome you know once in
a while try adding little extra oil into a vegetable like this especially with
spinach and then mix it with rice and eat I know you we'll feel guilty that we added
extra oil but the taste is really really heavenly now I'm going to add the spinach which
have shredded if you put the lid on you may lose that that's really nice
rich green color that is the reason why i'm cooking it open now even though i
reduce the flame little bit it may take another three minutes more but you know eating it with nice good
green color you know I really enjoyed that way you know the another way to cook is
because the potatoes take a little more time than the green leafy vegetables
first add potatoes and you can put the lid on so that this potatoes cook much faster. When the potatoes are almost eighty percent done then you add
the green leafy vegetable by the time the green leafy vegetables
are done your potatoes also will be hundred percent cooked and also you will
be able to retain the green color and cook it fast you know if you require you may add a
little water now these potatoes and the green leaf are very well cooked now I'm going to add a little bit of
coriander powder, chilli powder and salt haha this is a really spicy spinach and potato but remember that
always add little less salt than what you think will be required when you're
cooking spinach because spinach naturally has salts so adding very
little salt itself will make it perfect look at this spinach and potatoes perfectly done so let me taste I hope I did not add too
much salt i know i added little extra oil but ah nice flavor even though i added less salt the salt
is you know actually a little more than what I eat but perfect good, Dear friends I hope you enjoyed today's session of learning the spinach and potato with your VahChef but remember vahrehvah is all about
